answers.body_markdown:
The error states `error: Uncaught SyntaxError: Unexpected token &#39;export&#39;`, meaning that the JavaScript parser failed. It&#39;s not a Three.js error.

According to your link [WebGL compatibility check](https://threejs.org/docs/#manual/en/introduction/WebGL-compatibility-check), the code you imported is a JavaScript ES module.
Take a look at [this line](https://github.com/mrdoob/three.js/blob/master/examples/jsm/WebGL.js#L98). This line uses the `export` keyword, used to export a module. Thus, you are dealing with a module here and not a classic JS script.

If you want to include a module and not a simple script, you need to use:
```javascript
&lt;script src=&quot;js/three.js&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;script type=&quot;module&quot;&gt;
  import { WebGL } from &#39;js/WebGL.js&#39;;
  if ( WEBGL.isWebGLAvailable() ) {
    // ...
  }
&lt;/script&gt;
```

You can also directly use the WebGL script file instead of the JS module, if that&#39;s easier for you. You can find it [here](https://github.com/mrdoob/three.js/blob/dev/examples/jsm/WebGL.js).
Then, you should be able to access the `WEBGL` namespace like that:
```javascript
if ( THREE.WEBGL.isWebGLAvailable() ) {

  // WebGL is available

} else {

  // WebGL isn&#39;t available :(

}
```

I would recommend that you read the difference between a JS script and modules. For instance [here](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Guide/Modules).

